import json
from pathlib import Path

ROOT = Path(__file__).resolve().parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

NEW = {
  "18": {
    "1": "<p class=\"christ-type\">The synchronistic opening — <em>bišnat šāloš lᵉhôšēaʿ ben ʾēlāh melek yiśrāʾēl mālak ḥizqiyyāhû</em>, &lsquo;in the third year of Hoshea son of Elah king of Israel, Hezekiah began to reign&rsquo; — sets Hezekiah&rsquo;s enthronement within the final years of the northern kingdom. The best Davidic king rises precisely as Israel&rsquo;s collapse becomes irreversible. This is the pattern Paul names in Gal 4:4: <em>hote de ēlthen to plērōma tou chronou, exapesteilen ho theos ton hyion autou</em> — &lsquo;when the fullness of time had come, God sent forth his Son.&rsquo; The Son entered not when the world was at its best but at its crisis point. Hezekiah&rsquo;s timing within the Davidic sequence anticipates the timing of Christ&rsquo;s advent: the faithful king arrives when faithfulness is most scarce.</p>",
    "2": "<p class=\"christ-type\">Hezekiah was twenty-five years old when he began to reign, and he reigned twenty-nine years. The genealogical notation — his mother Abi, daughter of Zechariah — anchors him in the Davidic line. That Hezekiah&rsquo;s mother&rsquo;s name is recorded follows the pattern for Judahite kings throughout the DtrH; the absence of the mother&rsquo;s name in northern king notices marks a contrast between dynasties. Christ&rsquo;s own human genealogy (Matt 1:1-17; Luke 3:23-38) traces his lineage through this same Davidic chain, including the mothers and foreign women whose inclusion signals the breadth of the covenant people.</p>",
    "3": "<p class=\"christ-type\">The narrator&rsquo;s verdict — <em>wayyaʿaś hayyāšār bᵉʿênê YHWH kᵉḵōl ʾăšer ʿāśāh dāwid ʾāḇîw</em>, &lsquo;he did what was right in the eyes of YHWH, according to all that David his father had done&rsquo; — applies the highest royal standard: conformity to David. In the DtrH&rsquo;s royal assessment rubric, this phrase occurs only for Asa (1 Kgs 15:11) and Hezekiah; the next chapter will add that none were like Hezekiah before or after. The standard itself, however, is retrospective and partial — David&rsquo;s obedience was real but marred by Bathsheba and Uriah. The standard that the formula sets points forward to one who would fulfil it without qualification. John 8:29 records Jesus&rsquo;s own self-assessment: <em>hoti egō ta aresta autō poiō pantote</em> — &lsquo;for I always do the things that are pleasing to him.&rsquo; No Davidic king could say &lsquo;always.&rsquo;</p>",
    "4": "<p class=\"christ-type\">The destruction of Nehushtan — <em>hûʾ pittaṯ nᵉḥaš hannᵉḥōšet ʾăšer ʿāśāh mōšeh</em>, &lsquo;he broke in pieces the bronze serpent that Moses had made&rsquo; — is the most theologically laden of Hezekiah&rsquo;s reforms. The bronze serpent of Num 21:8-9 is the very object Jesus cites in John 3:14-15: <em>kai kathōs Mōysēs hypsōsen ton ophin en tē erēmō, houtōs hypsōthenai dei ton hyion tou anthrōpou</em> — &lsquo;as Moses lifted up the serpent in the wilderness, so must the Son of Man be lifted up.&rsquo; Jesus identifies himself as the antitype of the bronze serpent: he is lifted up on the cross to give life to all who look to him in faith. Hezekiah&rsquo;s destruction of the serpent as an idol teaches a further Christological principle: the type must not become an object of worship in place of the reality it signifies. The serpent-on-a-pole was a legitimate prefiguration of Christ crucified, but when Israel burned incense to it — <em>kî ʿaḏ hayyāmîm hāhēmmāh hāyû ḇᵉnê yiśrāʾēl mᵉqaṭṭᵉrîm lô</em> — it had become an idol displacing the reality it once pointed toward. The law of types is that they must give way when the antitype arrives; Hezekiah enforces this rule five centuries early.</p>",
    "6": "<p class=\"christ-type\">The double formulation — <em>wayyiḏḇaq baYHWH lōʾ sār mēʾaḥărāyw wayyišmōr miṣwōṯāyw</em>, &lsquo;he clung to YHWH; he did not depart from following him but kept his commandments&rsquo; — describes a fidelity that the DtrH presents as humanly exemplary but structurally incomplete. Heb 5:8 says of Christ: <em>emathen aph&rsquo; hōn epathen tēn hypakoēn</em> — &lsquo;he learned obedience through what he suffered.&rsquo; Hezekiah&rsquo;s clinging is real but will be tested and found wanting by Babylon&rsquo;s envoys (ch 20); Christ&rsquo;s obedience was tested in Gethsemane and at Calvary and did not waver. The same word-root appears in Deut 10:20 where Israel is commanded to <em>ûḇô ṯiḏḇāq</em> — cling to God. Hezekiah fulfils the command more fully than any other king; Christ fulfils it as the obedient Son whose cling is eternal (John 10:30).</p>",
    "7": "<p class=\"christ-theme\">The pivotal statement — <em>wayhî YHWH ʿimmô bᵉḵōl ʾăšer yēṣēʾ yaśkîl</em>, &lsquo;the LORD was with him; in all that he went out he prospered&rsquo; — applies to Hezekiah the Immanuel formula first spoken prophetically by Isaiah (Isa 7:14: <em>wᵉqārāʾṯ šᵉmô ʿimmānûʾēl</em>). Matthew quotes Isa 7:14 as the defining name of Jesus: <em>kai kalesousin to onoma autou Emmanouel, ho estin methermēneuomenon Meth&rsquo; hēmōn ho theos</em> — &lsquo;they shall call his name Immanuel, which means God with us&rsquo; (Matt 1:23). The formula &lsquo;the LORD was with him&rsquo; reaches through Hezekiah&rsquo;s reign to its ultimate fulfilment: not merely the LORD accompanying a king, but the LORD becoming flesh and tabernacling with his people (John 1:14). Matthew closes his Gospel with the risen Christ&rsquo;s promise: <em>kai idou egō meth&rsquo; hymōn eimi pasas tas hēmeras heōs tēs synteleias tou aiōnos</em> — &lsquo;behold I am with you always, to the end of the age&rsquo; (Matt 28:20).</p>",
    "8": "<p class=\"christ-type\">Hezekiah&rsquo;s military campaign — smiting the Philistines from watchtower to fortified city, from Gaza to its border — extends the Davidic mandate of subduing Israel&rsquo;s historic enemies. The faithful Davidic king is a warrior-king, and the DtrH evaluates his sovereignty partly by his military victories over the surrounding nations. This pattern of the royal warrior who defeats the enemies of God&rsquo;s people finds its fullest expression in Heb 2:14: <em>hina dia tou thanatou katargēsē ton to kratos echonta tou thanatou tout&rsquo; estin ton diabolon</em> — &lsquo;that through death he might destroy the one who has the power of death, that is, the devil.&rsquo; Christ&rsquo;s warfare is waged not with sword against Philistines but with death against the last enemy (1 Cor 15:26).</p>",
    "9": "<p class=\"christ-shadow\">The recapitulation of the Assyrian siege of Samaria — beginning in the fourth year of Hezekiah, the seventh of Hoshea — serves as a theological foil for what follows. The narrator reprises the northern collapse (vv9-12) immediately before Sennacherib&rsquo;s campaign against Judah (v13) to establish a stark contrast: Israel fell because of disobedience; will Judah? The exile of Israel is typologically related to Christ&rsquo;s identification with exile-bearing in Matt 27:46, where Jesus cries <em>Eli Eli lema sabachthani</em> — quoting Ps 22:1, the cry of the abandoned — thereby taking the curse of covenant-breaking exile into himself (Gal 3:13: <em>Christos hēmas exēgorasen ek tēs kataras tou nomou genomenos hyper hēmōn katara</em>).</p>",
    "10": "<p class=\"christ-shadow\">After three years the Assyrians took Samaria — <em>wayyilkᵉḏûhā miqṣēh šāloš šānîm</em>. The fall of Samaria in 722 BCE ended the northern kingdom permanently; its people were scattered to Halah, Habor, and the cities of the Medes (v11). This dispersion is what Jesus refers to when he weeps over the lost sheep of the house of Israel (Matt 15:24; 10:6), and what the Fourth Gospel understands his death to accomplish: <em>hina kai ta tekna tou theou ta dieskorpismena synagagē eis hen</em> — &lsquo;to gather into one the children of God who are scattered abroad&rsquo; (John 11:52). The three-year siege and final capture foreshadow a three-day death and resurrection that reverses the dispersion.</p>",
    "11": "<p class=\"christ-shadow\">The resettlement of Israel — <em>wayyaḡel ʾet yiśrāʾēl ʾaššûrāh wayyannîḥēm bᵉḥalaḥ ûḇᵉḥāḇôr</em> — describes a forced deportation that scattered the covenant people beyond recovery by any human political means. The ingathering of the exiles becomes a persistent eschatological hope (Isa 11:12; Jer 31:10; Ezek 37:21), and the NT locates its fulfilment in Christ. John 10:16 shows Jesus gathering those &lsquo;not of this fold&rsquo; into a single flock under one shepherd; Eph 1:10 describes God&rsquo;s plan: <em>anakephalaiōsasthai ta panta en tō Christō, ta epi tois ouranois kai ta epi tēs gēs</em> — &lsquo;to unite all things in Christ, things in heaven and things on earth.&rsquo; The exile of v11 defines the problem that Christ&rsquo;s gathering work solves.</p>",
    "12": "<p class=\"christ-direct\">The narrator&rsquo;s verdict on Israel&rsquo;s exile — <em>ʾăšer lōʾ šāmᵉʿû bᵉqôl YHWH ʾelōhêhem</em>, &lsquo;because they did not obey the voice of YHWH their God&rsquo; — identifies disobedience as the root cause of exile. The contrast with Christ is explicit in Heb 5:8-9: Christ &lsquo;learned obedience through what he suffered, and being made perfect he became the source of eternal salvation to all who obey him.&rsquo; Phil 2:8 formulates the same point as <em>genomenos hypēkoos mechri thanatou, thanatou de staurou</em> — &lsquo;becoming obedient to the point of death, even death on a cross.&rsquo; Israel&rsquo;s history of disobedience, which culminated in exile, is the negative ground against which Christ&rsquo;s obedience stands in relief. He heard the voice of the Father where Israel would not.</p>",
    "13": "<p class=\"christ-type\">Sennacherib&rsquo;s campaign against &lsquo;all the fenced cities of Judah&rsquo; in Hezekiah&rsquo;s fourteenth year creates the siege setting for the rest of the chapter. Archaeological evidence from Sennacherib&rsquo;s Annals confirms the campaign (701 BCE) and records his claim to have taken 46 fortified cities. The faithful Davidic king, who has done all that was right, now faces an overwhelming military threat that no human strength can answer. This is typologically parallel to Gethsemane: the most faithful king faces the most overwhelming crisis. Heb 6:18 speaks of Christ as the &lsquo;refuge&rsquo; — <em>kataphygōmen kratēsai tēs prokeimenes elpidos</em> — to which we flee, the fortified city that cannot be taken by any enemy.</p>",
    "14": "<p class=\"christ-type\">Hezekiah&rsquo;s tribute — three hundred talents of silver and thirty talents of gold stripped from the temple and the palace treasury — represents the king&rsquo;s humiliation before superior power. He strips the temple doors of their gold overlay to appease Sennacherib, and the text records it without comment: this is what faithfulness looks like when pressed against imperial force. The parallel with the Passion narrative is not incidental: at Calvary the soldiers stripped Jesus of his garments (Matt 27:28: <em>kai ekdysantes auton chlamy</em>da), and the crowd mocked his kingship. Both king and King are despoiled before the powers — but in Jesus&rsquo;s case the despoiling is the instrument of redemption, not merely its context (Col 2:15).</p>",
    "15": "<p class=\"christ-type\">The phrase &lsquo;all the silver that was found in the house of YHWH and in the treasuries of the king&rsquo;s house&rsquo; — <em>kol hakkesef hannimṣāʾ bêt YHWH ûbᵉʾôṣᵉrôt bêt hammelek</em> — marks the complete depletion of the sanctuary&rsquo;s accumulated wealth. The temple treasury had been built up over generations, from David&rsquo;s preparations through Solomon&rsquo;s construction and the subsequent offerings of faithful kings. Its emptying is the economic sign of the covenant community at its lowest ebb. Jesus in John 2:19-21 identifies his body as the true temple — <em>lysate ton naon touton kai en trisin hēmerais egerō auton</em> — so that the despoiling of the Solomonic temple finds its antitype in the despoiling of Christ&rsquo;s body, which was &lsquo;torn down&rsquo; only to be raised in three days.</p>",
    "16": "<p class=\"christ-type\">The stripping of the gold overlays from the temple doors and doorposts — gold that Hezekiah himself had placed there — makes the despoiling personal: the king removes what he himself dedicated. The temple is being undone by the same hand that honoured it. Hebrews&rsquo; temple theology reads this kind of depletion as pointing toward Christ: the true sanctuary is not made with hands (Heb 9:11), and the Levitical system of gold and offerings is superseded by the one sacrifice of Jesus Christ (Heb 10:14). The temple&rsquo;s gold could be stripped; the eternal sanctuary of Christ&rsquo;s high-priestly ministry cannot be exhausted or taken away (Heb 7:24: <em>ho de dia to menein auton eis ton aiōna aparabaton echei tēn hierōsynēn</em>).</p>",
    "17": "<p class=\"christ-shadow\">The Assyrian army encamps at the conduit of the upper pool on the highway of the Washer&rsquo;s Field — <em>ʿal tᵉʿālat habᵉrēḵāh hāʿelyônāh ʾăšer bᵉmesillat śᵉḏēh kôḇēs</em> — the same location where Isaiah met Ahaz in Isa 7:3 and where, according to John 9:7, the pool of Siloam lay nearby. Jesus sent the man born blind to wash in the pool of Siloam (John 9:7: <em>hgage nipsai eis tēn kolymb</em>ēthan tou Siloam), and the word means &lsquo;sent.&rsquo; The place where Assyrian troops camped to intimidate Jerusalem becomes the place where the one &lsquo;sent&rsquo; by the Father opened the eyes of the blind. Geography carries typological memory: threat-sites become grace-sites in the economy of redemption.</p>",
    "18": "<p class=\"christ-type\">Eliakim, Shebna, and Joah come out to meet Rabshakeh — the palace administrator, the secretary, and the recorder standing as representatives of Hezekiah&rsquo;s court before the Assyrian field commander. This scene of royal representatives standing before a hostile imperial power finds its fullest antitype in John 18-19: Jesus standing before Pilate, Caiaphas, and Herod. The parallel is not in the details but in the structure — the true King&rsquo;s representatives (and ultimately the King himself) face the world&rsquo;s imperial claim with no military backing, dependent entirely on the word of God. Isa 22:20-22, the oracle about Eliakim son of Hilkiah, is itself read messianically in Rev 3:7 (the key of David given to Christ: <em>ho echōn tēn kleida Dauid</em>).</p>",
    "19": "<p class=\"christ-direct\">Rabshakeh&rsquo;s challenge — <em>mah habbiṭṭāḥôn hazzeh ʾăšer bāṭāḥtā</em>, &lsquo;what is this confidence in which you trust?&rsquo; — is the formal question of the ancient Near Eastern propaganda speech, designed to destabilize the besieged city&rsquo;s psychology. In Matt 27:43 the same challenge echoes at Calvary: <em>pepoithen epi ton theon, rhysastho nyn auton ei thelei auton</em> — &lsquo;he trusts in God; let God deliver him now, if he desires him.&rsquo; The Matthean crowd&rsquo;s taunt at the cross is a direct allusion to Ps 22:8, but the rhetorical structure matches Rabshakeh&rsquo;s challenge: the confidence of the faithful person before God is mocked as naive by those who have military power. Both Hezekiah and Jesus answer the challenge not with counter-rhetoric but with prayer and waiting (Hezekiah, 19:14-19; Jesus, Matt 26:39-44).</p>",
    "20": "<p class=\"christ-theme\">Rabshakeh&rsquo;s dismissal — &lsquo;you say you have counsel and strength for war, but they are empty words&rsquo; — is the logic of every worldly power confronted with the claim that trust in God constitutes a viable strategy. Paul inverts this logic in 1 Cor 1:18-25: <em>hoti hē mōria tou theou sophōteron tōn anthrōpōn estin kai to asthenes tou theou ischyroteron tōn anthrōpōn estin</em> — &lsquo;the foolishness of God is wiser than men, and the weakness of God is stronger than men.&rsquo; The cross appeared to the Roman and Jewish establishment as precisely the kind of &lsquo;empty words&rsquo; that Rabshakeh dismisses — a crucified king offers no counsel and no strength. But in the resurrection God vindicates what looked like empty words.</p>",
    "21": "<p class=\"christ-theme\">The broken reed of Egypt — <em>ʿal mišʿenet haqāne hārāṣûṣ hazzeh ʿal miṣrayim ʾăšer yismāk ʾîš ʿālāyw ûḇāʾ bᵉkappô ûnᵉqāḇāh</em>, &lsquo;this broken reed of a staff, Egypt, on which if a man leans it will go into his hand and pierce it&rsquo; — is Rabshakeh&rsquo;s accurate analysis of Egypt as an unreliable ally. But his conclusion — &lsquo;and so is Pharaoh king of Egypt to all who trust in him&rsquo; — also functions as a universal description of every human savior. Acts 4:12 formulates the positive claim: <em>kai ouk estin en allō oudeni hē sōtēria</em> — &lsquo;and there is salvation in no one else, for there is no other name under heaven given among men by which we must be saved.&rsquo; The negative side of Acts 4:12 is Rabshakeh&rsquo;s catalogue: Egypt fails, then where else? Every reed breaks; the cross alone holds.</p>",
    "22": "<p class=\"christ-type\">Rabshakeh&rsquo;s twist — &lsquo;if you say to me, we trust in the LORD our God, is it not he whose high places and altars Hezekiah has removed?&rsquo; — deliberately misrepresents Hezekiah&rsquo;s reform as an act of impiety rather than fidelity. The propaganda strategy is to make the very thing that constituted Hezekiah&rsquo;s faithfulness appear as the reason God would not help him. At the cross, the same rhetorical structure appears: Jesus was accused of threatening the temple (Matt 26:61), the very place whose purity he had defended (John 2:17). The faithful act — reforming worship, cleansing the sanctuary — is weaponised as evidence of unworthiness.</p>",
    "23": "<p class=\"christ-theme\">Rabshakeh&rsquo;s ironic dare — &lsquo;give pledges to my master the king of Assyria; I will give you two thousand horses if you can put riders on them&rsquo; — highlights the military impossibility of Judah&rsquo;s position. The power differential is undeniable. The Passion narrative presents the same dynamic: the disciples flee, Peter denies, and no human power comes to Jesus&rsquo;s aid. Paul&rsquo;s logic in 1 Cor 1:27-28 runs counter to both Rabshakeh and common sense: <em>alla ta mōra tou kosmou exelexato ho theos hina kataischynē tous sophous</em> — &lsquo;God chose what is foolish in the world to shame the wise.&rsquo; God&rsquo;s answer to the horse-deficit is not cavalry but a single angel (19:35).</p>",
    "24": "<p class=\"christ-theme\">The rhetorical question — &lsquo;how then can you repulse even one captain among the least of my master&rsquo;s servants?&rsquo; — escalates the mockery: not merely Egypt&rsquo;s army but a single low-ranking Assyrian officer is more than Judah can handle. The taunt mirrors the crucifixion crowd&rsquo;s challenge in Luke 23:35-39: &lsquo;he saved others; let him save himself&rsquo; and &lsquo;save yourself and us.&rsquo; The structure of both taunts is identical — you cannot even handle the minor powers; how can you claim divine protection? The answer in both cases is the same: God&rsquo;s power operates through apparent weakness (2 Cor 12:9: <em>hē dynamis en astheneia teleitai</em>).</p>",
    "25": "<p class=\"christ-shadow\">Rabshakeh&rsquo;s most audacious claim — <em>YHWH ʾāmar ʾēlay ʿălēh ʿal hāʾāreṣ hazzōʾt wᵉhašḥîtāh</em>, &lsquo;the LORD said to me, go up against this land and destroy it&rsquo; — is either propaganda or a distorted echo of Isa 10:5-6, where God does call Assyria &lsquo;the rod of my anger.&rsquo; In either case, the verse raises the question of how God can use an evil instrument. Acts 2:23 articulates this principle most sharply in relation to the cross: <em>touton tē hōrismenē boulē kai prognōsei tou theou ekdoton dia cheiros anomōn proskollēsantes aneilate</em> — &lsquo;this Jesus, delivered up according to the definite plan and foreknowledge of God, you crucified and killed by the hands of lawless men.&rsquo; God uses Assyria; God uses Rome; in neither case does the human agent escape moral responsibility, and in neither case does God&rsquo;s sovereignty become the agent&rsquo;s excuse.</p>",
    "26": "<p class=\"christ-theme\">Eliakim, Shebna, and Joah ask Rabshakeh to speak Aramaic — the diplomatic language — rather than Hebrew, so the people on the wall cannot hear. The officials fear the psychological effect of the propaganda on the population. Rabshakeh refuses: he has come to speak precisely to the people, not only to the officials. The contrast with Jesus is instructive: Jesus taught publicly in the temple courts and in synagogues, refusing the secrecy that the powerful preferred. John 18:20: <em>egō parrēsiā lelalēka tō kosmō, egō pantote edidaxa en synagōgē kai en tō hierō</em> — &lsquo;I have spoken openly to the world; I have always taught in synagogues and in the temple.&rsquo;</p>",
    "27": "<p class=\"christ-theme\">Rabshakeh&rsquo;s crude response — specifying that he has come to speak to the men on the wall &lsquo;who will eat their own dung and drink their own urine&rsquo; — is designed to make the coming siege vivid and terrifying. The degradation of siege conditions was a real threat; Rabshakeh uses it to shatter morale. Phil 2:7-8 describes Christ&rsquo;s descent in opposite terms: not degrading others by threat but degrading himself by choice — <em>heauton ekenōsen morphēn doulou labōn... etapeinōsen heauton genomenos hypēkoos mechri thanatou, thanatou de staurou</em> — &lsquo;he emptied himself, taking the form of a servant... he humbled himself by becoming obedient to the point of death, even death on a cross.&rsquo; Christ&rsquo;s response to imperial power was not intimidation but incarnation.</p>",
    "28": "<p class=\"christ-direct\">Rabshakeh stands and cries with a loud voice in Hebrew — <em>wayyiqrāʾ bᵉqôl gāḏôl bᵉyᵉhûḏît wayyᵉḏabbēr wayyōʾmer</em> — and announces: &lsquo;hear the word of the great king, the king of Assyria.&rsquo; The &lsquo;great king&rsquo; title (<em>melek gadol</em>) was the standard Assyrian royal epithet (<em>šarru rabbu</em>). Rev 19:16 inscribes on the rider of the white horse a different title: <em>Basileus basileōn kai Kyrios kyriōn</em> — &lsquo;King of kings and Lord of lords.&rsquo; The Assyrian &lsquo;great king&rsquo; who threatens Jerusalem with a loud voice finds his antithesis in Christ, who speaks with authority (Matt 7:29) and before whom every knee will bow (Phil 2:10).</p>",
    "29": "<p class=\"christ-direct\">Rabshakeh&rsquo;s claim — &lsquo;let not Hezekiah deceive you, for he will not be able to deliver you from my hand&rsquo; — is the propaganda version of what the chief priests and scribes shout at the cross in Matt 27:42: <em>allous esōsen, heauton ou dynatai sōsai</em> — &lsquo;he saved others; he cannot save himself.&rsquo; In both cases the taunt assumes that inability to overpower the visible threat constitutes proof of divine abandonment. In both cases the taunt is answered not by immediate military rescue but by God&rsquo;s vindication through seemingly impossible means — one night, an angel (19:35); on the third day, resurrection. The claim &lsquo;he cannot deliver you&rsquo; is the one claim the cross appears to confirm and the resurrection definitively refutes.</p>",
    "30": "<p class=\"christ-direct\">The next accusation — that Hezekiah is making Israel trust in the LORD with the promise &lsquo;the LORD will surely deliver us, and this city will not be given into the hand of the king of Assyria&rsquo; — frames genuine faith as naive gullibility. Matt 27:43 continues the taunt pattern: <em>pepoithen epi ton theon, rhysastho nyn ei thelei auton</em> — &lsquo;he trusts in God; let God deliver him now, if he desires him.&rsquo; The crowd at Golgotha echoes Rabshakeh at Jerusalem: the confidence that God will deliver is treated as the proof of self-delusion. The Resurrection is the answer to both taunts simultaneously — the one hung on the cross and the king who trusted within the besieged city both discover that the promise of deliverance was not self-delusion.</p>",
    "31": "<p class=\"christ-theme\">Rabshakeh&rsquo;s enticement — &lsquo;make your peace with me and come out to me; then every one of you will eat from his own vine and fig tree and drink from his own cistern&rsquo; — is a parody of the messianic peace (Mic 4:4: <em>wᵉyāšᵉḇû ʾîš taḥat gapnô wᵉtaḥat tᵉʾēnātô</em>). The Assyrian king offers the form of shalom — each man under his vine — while requiring submission to the destroyer. The devil&rsquo;s temptation of Jesus in Matt 4:8-9 follows the same structure: &lsquo;all these I will give you, if you will fall down and worship me.&rsquo; Christ refuses the parody-peace; Eph 2:14 names the real thing: <em>autos gar estin hē eirēnē hēmōn</em> — &lsquo;for he himself is our peace.&rsquo;</p>",
    "32": "<p class=\"christ-shadow\">The rhetoric escalates: &lsquo;until I come and take you to a land like your own land, a land of grain and wine, a land of bread and vineyards.&rsquo; Sennacherib&rsquo;s false promise of exile as bounty inverts the covenant geography — the land of YHWH&rsquo;s gift replaced by deportation to Assyria dressed up in the language of plenty. Jesus&rsquo;s promise in John 14:2-3 uses a related spatial language but with opposite valence: <em>poresomai hetoimasai topon hymin... palin erchomai kai paralēmpsomai hymas pros emauton</em> — &lsquo;I go to prepare a place for you... I will come again and will take you to myself.&rsquo; The true king&rsquo;s departure prepares a better home; the false king&rsquo;s arrival destroys the one already given.</p>",
    "33": "<p class=\"christ-direct\">The climactic rhetorical challenge — <em>hahaṣṣêl hiṣṣîlû ʾelōhê haggôyim ʾîš ʾet ʾarṣô miyyad melek ʾaššûr</em>, &lsquo;has any of the gods of the nations ever delivered his land out of the hand of the king of Assyria?&rsquo; — is the question that the resurrection answers. No pagan deity delivered its city from Assyria; but YHWH delivered Jerusalem. Beyond that, the resurrection declares that the ultimate imperial power — death itself — has been defeated. 1 Cor 15:54-57 announces: <em>katepothē ho thanatos eis nikos. pou sou, thanate, to nikos; pou sou, thanate, to kentron</em> — &lsquo;death is swallowed up in victory. O death, where is your victory? O death, where is your sting?&rsquo; The question &lsquo;has any god delivered?&rsquo; has one final answer: the God of Israel, in Christ, delivered from death itself.</p>",
    "34": "<p class=\"christ-direct\">The enumeration of fallen cities and their powerless gods — Hamath, Arpad, Sepharvaim, Hena, Ivvah — is Rabshakeh&rsquo;s evidence that YHWH is one deity among many equally unable to resist Assyrian arms. 1 Cor 15:24-27 maps the trajectory of Christ&rsquo;s final victory over all powers: <em>eita to telos hotan paradidō tēn basileian tō theō kai patri, hotan katargēsē pasan archēn kai pasan exousian kai dynamin</em> — &lsquo;then comes the end, when he delivers the kingdom to God the Father after destroying every rule and every authority and power.&rsquo; The gods of Hamath and Arpad have already been silenced; Christ&rsquo;s resurrection begins the final campaign that ends when the last enemy — death — is also destroyed (1 Cor 15:26).</p>",
    "35": "<p class=\"christ-direct\">The implied question — &lsquo;who among all the gods of the countries has delivered his country from my hand, that the LORD should deliver Jerusalem?&rsquo; — is answered not by Hezekiah&rsquo;s rhetoric but by the event of 19:35. But beyond the single night deliverance of Jerusalem, the NT reads the Lord&rsquo;s deliverance of Jerusalem as a type of the ultimate deliverance: Acts 2:24 affirms that God &lsquo;raised him up, loosing the pangs of death, because it was not possible for him to be held by it&rsquo; — <em>hon ho theos anestēsen lysas tas ōdinas tou thanatou, kathoti ouk ēn dynaton krateisthai auton hyp&rsquo; autou</em>. The &lsquo;not possible&rsquo; of the resurrection answers Rabshakeh&rsquo;s &lsquo;who can?&rsquo; The answer is: the God who raised Jesus from the dead.</p>",
    "36": "<p class=\"christ-type\">The people&rsquo;s response — <em>wayyaḥărîšû hāʿām wᵉlōʾ ʿānû ʾōtô dāḇār</em>, &lsquo;the people were silent and answered him not a word, for the king&rsquo;s command was, do not answer him&rsquo; — presents a community holding its tongue under calculated provocation. Matt 27:14 describes Jesus before Pilate: <em>kai ouk apekrithē autō pros oude hen rhēma, hōste thaumazein ton hēgemona lian</em> — &lsquo;but he gave him no answer, not even to a single charge, so that the governor was greatly amazed.&rsquo; In both cases the silence is not weakness but strategic non-engagement with a question that the adversary has framed to make any answer a defeat. The king who commands silence and the King who chooses silence are types of the same wisdom: the moment for speech has not yet come.</p>",
    "37": "<p class=\"christ-shadow\">The chapter closes with Eliakim, Shebna, and Joah coming to Hezekiah with their clothes torn — the mourning gesture that signals the gravity of what Rabshakeh has said. Torn garments appear at the Passion: the high priest tears his robes at Jesus&rsquo;s answer about the Son of Man (Matt 26:65: <em>tote ho archiereus dierrēxen ta himatia autou</em>). The garment-tearing at Caiaphas&rsquo;s palace is officially a sign of blasphemy; the garment-tearing at Hezekiah&rsquo;s court is a sign of distress. In both cases the gesture marks the moment when the faithful community recognises that the crisis has reached its crisis — the point of decision that prayer alone can address.</p>"
  },
  "19": {
    "1": "<p class=\"christ-type\">Hezekiah&rsquo;s response to Rabshakeh&rsquo;s report — tearing his clothes, covering himself with sackcloth, and going into the house of YHWH — is the royal equivalent of Gethsemane. The king in the most extreme political crisis goes not to his generals but to the sanctuary. Mark 14:33-34 narrates Jesus entering Gethsemane: <em>kai ērxato ekthambeisthai kai adēmonein kai legei autois, Perilypos estin hē psychē mou heōs thanatou</em> — &lsquo;he began to be greatly distressed and troubled, and said to them, my soul is very sorrowful, even to death.&rsquo; Both kings — the type and the antitype — bring the full weight of their crisis into the presence of the Father. Hezekiah brings the torn garment; Jesus brings the &lsquo;cup.&rsquo; In both cases the crisis is irreducibly real; in both cases the response is prayer.</p>",
    "2": "<p class=\"christ-type\">Hezekiah sends the elders of the priests, covered with sackcloth, to Isaiah the prophet — <em>wayyišlaḥ ʾet ʾelyāqîm... wᵉʾēt šeḇnāʾ... wᵉʾēt ziqnê hakōhănîm mᵉkussîm śaqqîm ʾel yᵉšaʿyāhû hannāḇîʾ</em>. The king reaches for the prophetic word in the moment of crisis. This mediatorial structure — king seeking the prophet, who speaks God&rsquo;s word — is the OT framework that Christ collapses into one person. Jesus is simultaneously the one who prays (king in crisis), the one through whom God speaks (prophet), and the one who mediates access (priest). Heb 1:1-2 names the transition: <em>polymeros kai polytropōs palai ho theos lalēsas tois patrasin en tois prophētais ep&rsquo; eschatou tōn hēmerōn toutōn elalēsen hēmin en hyiō</em> — formerly through prophets; finally through the Son.</p>",
    "3": "<p class=\"christ-shadow\">The message brought to Isaiah — &lsquo;this day is a day of distress, rebuke, and dishonour; children have come to the point of birth, and there is no strength to bring them forth&rsquo; — describes a crisis that has reached the limit of human endurance without resolution. The birth-without-delivery image is anguish without relief. The Passion narrative is the ultimate &lsquo;day of distress and rebuke and dishonour&rsquo; (cf. Lam 1:12 &lsquo;is it nothing to you, all who pass by?&rsquo;). Mark 15:29-32 catalogues the blasphemies heaped on Jesus: the passers-by, the chief priests, the scribes, even the two criminals — all &lsquo;reviling him.&rsquo; The day of Golgotha is the antitype of the day of crisis Hezekiah names; in both cases the word of God is the only resource.</p>",
    "4": "<p class=\"christ-type\">Hezekiah&rsquo;s prayer request — &lsquo;it may be that the LORD your God heard all the words of Rabshakeh... therefore lift up your prayer for the remnant that is left&rsquo; — is an intercession request grounded in uncertainty (<em>ʾûlay</em>, &lsquo;perhaps&rsquo;). He does not know whether God will hear, but he asks. Christ&rsquo;s intercession knows no such uncertainty: Heb 7:25 says he &lsquo;always lives to make intercession&rsquo; — <em>pantote zōn eis to entynchanein hyper autōn</em> — and John 11:42 shows Jesus praying &lsquo;I knew that you always hear me.&rsquo; The &lsquo;perhaps&rsquo; of Hezekiah&rsquo;s request is replaced by the certainty of the Son&rsquo;s intercession for the remnant.</p>",
    "5": "<p class=\"christ-type\">The servants of Hezekiah come to Isaiah — the king&rsquo;s crisis requiring a prophetic intermediary. This structural dependence on mediation runs throughout the OT: king cannot access God directly in the moment of extreme need without the prophet. Christ ends the structural dependence on external mediation. 1 Tim 2:5 names him: <em>heis gar theos, heis kai mesitēs theou kai anthrōpōn, anthrōpos Christos Iēsous</em> — &lsquo;for there is one God, and there is one mediator between God and men, the man Christ Jesus.&rsquo; The prophets were mediators of the word; Christ is the mediator of the new covenant (Heb 9:15), in whom the separation that required intermediaries is abolished.</p>",
    "6": "<p class=\"christ-direct\">Isaiah&rsquo;s word — <em>kōh tōʾmar ʾel ʾăḏōnêḵem lōʾ tîrāʾ mippenê haddeḇārîm ʾăšer šāmaʿtā</em>, &lsquo;thus shall you say to your master: do not be afraid because of the words you have heard&rsquo; — employs the prophetic salvation oracle formula. &lsquo;Do not be afraid&rsquo; (<em>ʾal tîrāʾ</em>) is the characteristic word of divine arrival throughout the OT (Gen 15:1; Isa 41:10; 43:1). Jesus applies it to himself in Rev 1:17-18: <em>mē phobou; egō eimi ho prōtos kai ho eschatos kai ho zōn, kai egenomēn nekros, kai idou zōn eimi eis tous aiōnas tōn aiōnōn</em> — &lsquo;do not be afraid; I am the first and the last and the living one; I died, and behold I am alive forevermore.&rsquo; The salvation oracle that Isaiah brings from God is given by Christ from within the crisis of death and resurrection.</p>",
    "7": "<p class=\"christ-theme\">God&rsquo;s sovereign action against Sennacherib — &lsquo;I will put a spirit in him, so that he shall hear a rumor and return to his own land, and I will make him fall by the sword in his own land&rsquo; — operates through hidden providential means: a rumor, a return, a sword. God defeats the world&rsquo;s most powerful military force not by superior armies but by an inner prompting and a family member&rsquo;s blade (19:37). Rev 19:11-16 pictures Christ as the divine warrior whose &lsquo;sword&rsquo; is the word from his mouth — <em>kai ek tou stomatos autou ekporeuetai rhomphaia oxeia</em>. The method of divine warfare revealed in Sennacherib&rsquo;s defeat points toward the cross and resurrection, where God defeats the &lsquo;ruler of this world&rsquo; (John 12:31) not by force but by the apparently weak instrument of crucifixion.</p>",
    "8": "<p class=\"christ-theme\">Rabshakeh withdraws when he finds Sennacherib has left Lachish and is fighting at Libnah. The siege of Jerusalem is lifted not because of Judah&rsquo;s military power but because the enemy&rsquo;s attention is diverted. The image of the accuser who departs when challenged in a different direction anticipates John 8:9, where Jesus&rsquo;s challenge to the accusers — &lsquo;let him who is without sin among you be the first to throw a stone&rsquo; — causes them to leave &lsquo;one by one.&rsquo; The removal of the accusers is always God&rsquo;s work, whether through divine intervention in history or through the probing word of the Son of God.</p>",
    "9": "<p class=\"christ-theme\">The rumour of Tirhakah king of Ethiopia — help coming from an unexpected quarter in Africa — introduces a geopolitical complexity that relieves the pressure on Hezekiah. The help comes from outside the expected range of allies, from the south (Ethiopia/Kush) rather than from the west (Egypt). Paul&rsquo;s meditation on unexpected grace (1 Cor 1:27-28) captures the same structure: God chooses what is weak, what is low, what is despised — the foolish things to shame the wise. Christ himself is help from an unexpected source: not the military messiah expected by many, but the crucified one who conquers through weakness. The geography of grace is always surprising.</p>",
    "10": "<p class=\"christ-shadow\">Sennacherib&rsquo;s letter to Hezekiah — a written document of intimidation claiming that Hezekiah&rsquo;s God will not deliver Jerusalem — is a written accusation against the covenant community. Col 2:14 describes what Christ accomplishes at the cross in exactly these terms: <em>exaleipsas to kath&rsquo; hēmōn cheirographon tois dogmasin ho ēn hypenantionhēmin, kai auton ērken ek tou mesou, prosēlōsas auto tō staurō</em> — &lsquo;by canceling the record of debt that stood against us with its legal demands. This he set aside, nailing it to the cross.&rsquo; The written accusation that Hezekiah spreads before YHWH (v14) is the type of the written accusation that Christ nails to the cross.</p>",
    "11": "<p class=\"christ-direct\">The historical argument — &lsquo;behold, you have heard what the kings of Assyria have done to all lands, devoting them to destruction. And shall you be delivered?&rsquo; — assumes that historical precedent is determinative. But the resurrection breaks historical precedent entirely. Hebrews 1:1-2 marks the break: the former word came through prophets; the final word comes through the Son, whose resurrection is without precedent. The pattern &lsquo;what the kings did to all lands&rsquo; — death, destruction, exile — meets its absolute exception in Christ. No king of Assyria, Babylon, or Rome could be &lsquo;not held&rsquo; by death (Acts 2:24); Jesus alone breaks the pattern of historical necessity.</p>",
    "12": "<p class=\"christ-direct\">The enumeration of cities whose gods did not deliver them — Gozan, Haran, Rezeph, Eden — is the empirical catalogue of divine failure. Against this empirical list, Heb 1:1-2 sets the eschatological word: <em>ep&rsquo; eschatou tōn hēmerōn toutōn elalēsen hēmin en hyiō, hon ethēken klēronomon pantōn, di&rsquo; hou kai epoiēsen tous aiōnas</em> — &lsquo;in these last days he has spoken to us by his Son, whom he appointed the heir of all things, through whom also he created the world.&rsquo; The gods of Gozan and Haran were creatures of human hands; the Son through whom creation happened cannot be enumerated among them. The catalogue ends with Christ as its exception and refutation.</p>",
    "13": "<p class=\"christ-theme\">The roll-call of defeated kings — &lsquo;where is the king of Hamath, the king of Arpad, the king of the city of Sepharvaim, Hena, or Ivvah?&rsquo; — establishes the pattern: kings fall, kingdoms disappear, and history moves forward without them. Dan 7:14 breaks the pattern with the Son of Man&rsquo;s kingdom: <em>kai edothē autō exousia kai timē kai basileia, kai pantes hoi laoi phylai kai glōssai autō douleuousin; hē exousia autou exousia aiōnios hētis ou pareleusetai, kai hē basileia autou ou diaphtharsēsetai</em> — &lsquo;to him was given dominion and glory and a kingdom, that all peoples, nations, and languages should serve him; his dominion is an everlasting dominion, which shall not pass away.&rsquo; The kings of Hamath are in the &lsquo;where are they now?&rsquo; category; the Son of Man&rsquo;s kingdom is not.</p>",
    "14": "<p class=\"christ-type\">The gesture of spreading Sennacherib&rsquo;s letter before YHWH — <em>wayyipperehû ḥizqiyyāhû lipnê YHWH</em>, &lsquo;and Hezekiah spread it before the LORD&rsquo; — is one of the most vivid acts of prayer in the OT. The king takes the physical document of threat — the written imperial claim that God cannot deliver — and literally places it before God&rsquo;s eyes in the sanctuary. This is the enacted form of Heb 4:16: <em>proserchōmetha oun meta parrēsias tō thronō tēs charitos</em> — &lsquo;let us then with confidence draw near to the throne of grace.&rsquo; Hezekiah approaches the throne with the enemy&rsquo;s letter; the church approaches with its burdens and accusations. Christ has opened this access (Heb 10:19-22) by his blood, fulfilling what Hezekiah&rsquo;s gesture anticipated.</p>",
    "16": "<p class=\"christ-type\">Hezekiah&rsquo;s petition — <em>YHWH haṭṭēh ʾoznᵉḵā ûšᵉmaʿ pqaḥ YHWH ʿênêḵā ûrᵉʾēh</em>, &lsquo;O LORD, bow your ear and hear; O LORD, open your eyes and see&rsquo; — asks for attentiveness from the God who is enthroned above the cherubim. This is the petition of one whose access to the throne of God is mediated through the sanctuary. The prayer for God to &lsquo;see&rsquo; and &lsquo;hear&rsquo; assumes the possibility that God will act on what he perceives. Heb 4:16 invites the church to approach the throne of grace with boldness — <em>hina labōmen eleon kai charin heurōmen eis eukairo boētheian</em> — &lsquo;that we may receive mercy and find grace to help in time of need.&rsquo; Christ&rsquo;s high priesthood makes the petition of v16 not merely possible but assured.</p>",
    "17": "<p class=\"christ-shadow\">The honest acknowledgment — <em>ʾāmnām YHWH heḥĕrîḇû malkê ʾaššûr ʾet haggôyim wᵉʾet ʾarṣām</em>, &lsquo;truly, O LORD, the kings of Assyria have laid waste the nations and their lands&rsquo; — is a prayer that does not minimize the enemy&rsquo;s power. Hezekiah does not claim the threat is exaggerated. Similarly, the NT does not minimize the reality of death: Heb 2:14-15 describes Christ&rsquo;s mission as precisely confronting real death — <em>epei oun ta paidia kekoinōnēken haimatos kai sarkos, kai autos paraplēsiōs meteschen tōn autōn, hina dia tou thanatou katargēsē ton to kratos echonta tou thanatou</em>. The prayer of faith is not denial of the enemy&rsquo;s power; it is honest acknowledgment of it followed by appeal to the one whose power exceeds it.</p>",
    "18": "<p class=\"christ-theme\">The explanation for why Assyria succeeded — &lsquo;they were no gods, but the work of men&rsquo;s hands, wood and stone&rsquo; — identifies the root of pagan vulnerability: gods of human manufacture cannot save human beings. Heb 2:14 reads Christ&rsquo;s incarnation and death as the divine response to precisely this problem: only one who fully shares human flesh and blood can defeat the power that threatens human flesh and blood. &lsquo;Wood and stone&rsquo; gods are cast into fire; Christ himself enters into the death that destroys everything wooden and stony — and emerges from it. The living God enters the human condition to defeat the enemy that destroys human manufacture from within.</p>",
    "19": "<p class=\"christ-direct\">The petition&rsquo;s climax — <em>wᵉʿattāh YHWH ʾelōhênû hôšîʿēnû nāʾ miyyāḏô wᵉyēdᵉʿû kol mamléḵôt hāʾāreṣ kî ʾattāh YHWH ʾelōhîm lᵉḇaddᵉḵā</em>, &lsquo;so now, O LORD our God, save us, please, from his hand, so that all the kingdoms of the earth may know that you, O LORD, are God alone&rsquo; — grounds the request in the purpose of universal knowledge of God. Phil 2:9-11 describes the same universal recognition as the goal of Christ&rsquo;s exaltation: <em>hina en tō onomati Iēsou pan gony kampsē epouraniōn kai epigeiōn kai katachthoniōn kai pasa glōssa exomologēsētai hoti Kyrios Iēsous Christos eis doxan theou patros</em> — &lsquo;that at the name of Jesus every knee should bow... and every tongue confess that Jesus Christ is Lord.&rsquo; Hezekiah prays for Jerusalem&rsquo;s deliverance so the nations may know YHWH; the resurrection of Jesus delivers the universal knowledge Hezekiah prayed for.</p>",
    "20": "<p class=\"christ-type\">Isaiah&rsquo;s response — &lsquo;your prayer to me concerning Sennacherib king of Assyria I have heard&rsquo; — names the mechanism: prayer addressed to God and answered through the prophetic word. Heb 5:7 applies the same structure to Jesus: <em>hos en tais hēmerais tēs sarkos autou deēseis te kai hiketērias pros ton dynastamenon sōzein auton ek thanatou meta kraugēs ischyras kai dakryōn prosenenkas kai eisakoustheis apo tēs eulabeias</em> — &lsquo;in the days of his flesh, Jesus offered up prayers and supplications, with loud crying and tears, to him who was able to save him from death, and he was heard because of his reverent submission.&rsquo; Both Hezekiah and Jesus pray in extremity; both are heard. But Jesus&rsquo;s being heard means resurrection through death, not exemption from it.</p>",
    "21": "<p class=\"christ-type\">Isaiah&rsquo;s taunt-oracle — &lsquo;the virgin daughter of Zion despises you and mocks you; the daughter of Jerusalem wags her head behind you&rsquo; — presents Zion as the one who will have the last word over the proud empire. The image of the daughter of Zion standing confident against all human power is taken up in Eph 6:13: <em>analabete tēn panoplian tou theou, hina dynēthēte antistēnai en tē hēmera tē ponēra</em> — &lsquo;take up the whole armour of God, that you may be able to withstand in the evil day.&rsquo; The church&rsquo;s confidence before the powers of the age is rooted in Christ&rsquo;s victory — the antitype of Zion&rsquo;s mockery of Sennacherib. The daughter who mocks now is the bride who will reign (Rev 21:2).</p>",
    "22": "<p class=\"christ-direct\">The oracle turns directly to Sennacherib&rsquo;s offence: <em>ʾet mî ḥēraptāh ûḇēddaltāh... ʿal qᵉḏôš yiśrāʾēl</em>, &lsquo;whom have you mocked and reviled? And against whom have you raised your voice and lifted your eyes high? Against the Holy One of Israel.&rsquo; &lsquo;The Holy One of Israel&rsquo; is Isaiah&rsquo;s distinctive title for YHWH, but the NT applies it to Jesus: in Mark 1:24 the unclean spirit cries, <em>oida se tis ei, ho hagios tou theou</em> — &lsquo;I know who you are — the Holy One of God&rsquo;; and in Acts 3:14 Peter accuses Jerusalem: <em>hymeis de ton hagion kai dikaion ērnēsasthe</em> — &lsquo;but you denied the Holy and Righteous One.&rsquo; What Sennacherib did against the Holy One of Israel is what Jerusalem did against Jesus: reproached and denied the one whose holiness is the measure by which all other claims are judged.</p>",
    "23": "<p class=\"christ-theme\">Sennacherib&rsquo;s boast — &lsquo;with my many chariots I have gone up the heights of the mountains, to the far recesses of Lebanon; I will cut down its tallest cedars, its choicest firs&rsquo; — is the rhetoric of imperial pride. Jas 4:6 quotes Prov 3:34: <em>ho theos hyperēphanois antitassetai, tapeinois de didōsin charin</em> — &lsquo;God opposes the proud but gives grace to the humble.&rsquo; Sennacherib is the embodiment of the pride that God opposes; Christ is the embodiment of the humility that God exalts (Phil 2:5-9). The cedar-felling boast is the opposite of the cross; the one who climbs in pride is brought down, while the one who descends in humility is lifted up.</p>",
    "24": "<p class=\"christ-theme\">The boast continues: &lsquo;I dug wells and drank foreign waters; I dried up with the sole of my foot all the streams of Egypt.&rsquo; Self-sufficient access to water — the fundamental resource — is the metaphor of imperial mastery over the natural world. Against this self-sufficiency Jesus offers John 4:10: <em>ei ēdeis tēn dōrean tou theou kai tis estin ho legōn soi, Dos moi pein, sy an ētēsas auton kai edōken an soi hydōr zōn</em> — &lsquo;if you knew the gift of God and who it is that is saying to you, give me a drink, you would have asked him, and he would have given you living water.&rsquo; The king who boasts of digging cisterns and drinking everywhere meets the King who gives water that becomes a spring welling up to eternal life (John 4:14).</p>",
    "25": "<p class=\"christ-direct\">The most theologically dense verse of the oracle — <em>hălōʾ šāmaʿtā lᵉmērāḥôq ʾōtāh ʿāśîtî mîmê qedem wîṣartîhā</em>, &lsquo;have you not heard? Long ago I determined it; from ancient days I planned it; now I bring it to pass&rsquo; — reveals that Assyria&rsquo;s campaigns were within God&rsquo;s eternal purpose. The same divine sovereignty over evil instruments governs Acts 2:23: <em>touton tē hōrismenē boulē kai prognōsei tou theou ekdoton</em> — &lsquo;this Jesus, delivered up according to the definite plan and foreknowledge of God.&rsquo; God planned Assyria&rsquo;s rise long ago for his purposes; God planned the cross from before the foundation of the world (1 Pet 1:20: <em>proegnōsmenou men pro katabolēs kosmou</em>). The sovereign &lsquo;long ago I planned it&rsquo; applies to both Sennacherib&rsquo;s campaign and Calvary.</p>",
    "26": "<p class=\"christ-shadow\">The description of the nations before Sennacherib — &lsquo;their inhabitants, shorn of strength, were dismayed and confounded, and have become like plants of the field and like tender grass&rsquo; — is a picture of universal human fragility before imperial power. Heb 2:14-17 begins with the same diagnosis of the human condition: all share flesh and blood, all are subject to death&rsquo;s power. The solution is not human strength but incarnation: <em>kai autos paraplēsiōs meteschen tōn autōn</em> — &lsquo;and he himself partook of the same things.&rsquo; Christ enters the grass-like fragility of human existence precisely to rescue it from within. The nations who wilt before Sennacherib are the humanity Christ became to save.</p>",
    "27": "<p class=\"christ-theme\">God&rsquo;s declaration of omniscience over Sennacherib — <em>wᵉšiḇtᵉḵā wᵉṣēʾtᵉḵā ûḇôʾᵉḵā yāḏaʿtî wᵉʾēt hiṯragzᵉḵā ʾēlay</em>, &lsquo;I know your sitting down and your going out and coming in, and your raging against me&rsquo; — applies to the proud king the same sovereign knowledge that Christ claims over all human hearts. John 2:25: <em>kai hoti ou chreian eichen hina tis martyrēsē peri tou anthrōpou, autos gar eginōsken ti ēn en tō anthrōpō</em> — &lsquo;and he needed no one to bear witness about man, for he himself knew what was in man.&rsquo; What YHWH knows about Sennacherib&rsquo;s inner raging, Christ knows about every human heart. This omniscience is not threat but comfort: the one who knows all things intercedes for us (Heb 7:25).</p>",
    "28": "<p class=\"christ-type\">The divine verdict — &lsquo;because you have raged against me and your tumult has come to my ears, I will put my hook in your nose and my bridle on your lips, and I will turn you back on the way by which you came&rsquo; — images God&rsquo;s sovereign control over the proudest empire as a trainer controls an animal. Matt 28:18 establishes Christ&rsquo;s authority over all powers: <em>edothē moi pasa exousia en ouranō kai epi gēs</em> — &lsquo;all authority in heaven and on earth has been given to me.&rsquo; The hook in the nose of Sennacherib is the particular, historical expression of the universal authority that the risen Christ holds. No power — not Assyrian, not Roman, not demonic — exceeds the span of his sovereignty.</p>",
    "29": "<p class=\"christ-type\">The agricultural sign for Hezekiah — &lsquo;this year eat what grows of itself, and in the second year what springs from the same; then in the third year sow and reap, and plant vineyards and eat their fruit&rsquo; — describes a sabbatical-year pattern of provision: the land yields without human effort while the people wait for the enemy to depart. The provision without sowing anticipates the grace of the kingdom: not what human effort produces but what God gives freely. Mark 4:26-29 uses the same agricultural imagery for the kingdom: <em>houtōs estin hē basileia tou theou hōs anthrōpos balē ton sporon epi tēs gēs kai katheuē kai egeirētai, kai ho sporos blasta kai mēkynētai hōs ouk oiden autos</em> — the seed grows &lsquo;he knows not how.&rsquo; God&rsquo;s provision does not wait on human effort.</p>",
    "30": "<p class=\"christ-direct\">The remnant oracle — <em>wᵉyāsᵉpāh pelêṭat bêt yᵉhûḏāh hannišʾāret šōreš lᵉmaṭṭāh wᵉʿāśāh perî lᵉmaʿlāh</em>, &lsquo;and the surviving remnant of the house of Judah shall again take root downward and bear fruit upward&rsquo; — is the royal-botanical image that Isaiah develops in Isa 11:1: <em>wᵉyāṣāʾ ḥōṭer miggezaʿ yišay wᵉnēṣer miššorāšāyw yipreh</em> — &lsquo;there shall come forth a shoot from the stump of Jesse, and a branch from his roots shall bear fruit.&rsquo; Paul in Rom 15:12 quotes Isa 11:10 of Christ: <em>ho rhiza tou Iessai kai ho anistamenos archein ethnōn, ep&rsquo; autō ethnē elpiousin</em> — &lsquo;the root of Jesse, who rises to rule the Gentiles; in him will the Gentiles hope.&rsquo; The remnant that takes root in v30 is ultimately the Davidic root — Jesus — from whom the final, imperishable fruit grows.</p>",
    "31": "<p class=\"christ-direct\">The guarantee of the remnant oracle — <em>qinʾat YHWH ṣᵉḇāʾôt taʿăśeh zōʾṯ</em>, &lsquo;the zeal of the LORD of hosts will accomplish this&rsquo; — is the exact phrase cited by John 2:17 of Jesus&rsquo;s temple action: <em>hoi mathētai autou emnēsthēsan hoti gegrammenon estin, Ho zēlos tou oikou sou kataphagetal me</em> — &lsquo;his disciples remembered that it was written, zeal for your house will consume me&rsquo; (citing Ps 69:9). The divine zeal that accomplishes the deliverance of Jerusalem and the growth of the remnant is the same zeal that drives Jesus&rsquo;s temple cleansing — and ultimately his cross. The word <em>qinʾāh</em>/zeal carries the force of jealous, passionate, consuming commitment. In Christ, the Father&rsquo;s zeal for his house became the Son&rsquo;s zeal for his Father, which consumed him on the cross.</p>",
    "32": "<p class=\"christ-type\">The promise for Jerusalem — &lsquo;he shall not come into this city or shoot an arrow there; he shall not come before it with a shield or cast up a siege mound against it&rsquo; — describes the city that the enemy cannot breach. John 10:9 presents Christ as the gate of the sheepfold: <em>egō eimi hē thyra; di&rsquo; emou ean tis eiselthē sōthēsetai</em> — &lsquo;I am the door; if anyone enters by me, he will be saved.&rsquo; Those who enter through Christ enter a city the enemy cannot breach. Gal 5:1: <em>tē eleutherias hēmas Christos ēleutherōsen; stēkete oun kai mē palin zygō douleias enechesthe</em> — &lsquo;for freedom Christ has set us free; stand firm therefore.&rsquo; The freedom from siege promised to Jerusalem is the type of the freedom from every enemy that Christ secures.</p>",
    "33": "<p class=\"christ-theme\">The reversal — &lsquo;by the way that he came, by the same he shall return, and he shall not come into this city&rsquo; — describes the enemy turned back at the threshold. The resurrection of Christ is the ultimate reversal of the enemy&rsquo;s advance: death, which entered human life through the fall, is turned back at the empty tomb. 1 Cor 15:21-22 maps the reversal: <em>epeidē gar di&rsquo; anthrōpou thanatos, kai di&rsquo; anthrōpou anastasis nekrōn</em> — &lsquo;for as by a man came death, by a man has come also the resurrection of the dead.&rsquo; The way death came is the way it departs — reversed by a man, but the man who is also God.</p>",
    "34": "<p class=\"christ-direct\">The basis for Jerusalem&rsquo;s deliverance — <em>wᵉgannôtî ʿal hāʿîr hazzōʾṯ lᵉhôšîʿāh lᵉmaʿănî ûlᵉmaʿan dāwid ʿaḇdî</em>, &lsquo;for I will defend this city to save it, for my own sake and for the sake of David my servant&rsquo; — grounds the deliverance in two things simultaneously: God&rsquo;s own name and the Davidic covenant. Acts 2:30-31 anchors the resurrection in exactly the same Davidic covenant: &lsquo;knowing that God had sworn with an oath to him that he would set one of his descendants on his throne, he foresaw and spoke about the resurrection of the Christ.&rsquo; God defends Jerusalem for David&rsquo;s sake; God raises Jesus for the same reason — to fulfil the oath sworn to David. The Davidic covenant is not merely a dynastic arrangement but an eternal commitment that the resurrection fulfils.</p>",
    "35": "<p class=\"christ-theme\">The angel of YHWH destroying 185,000 in a single night — <em>wayyēṣēʾ malʾaḵ YHWH wayyaḵ bᵉmaḥănēh ʾaššûr mēʾāh šᵉmônîm wᵉḥāmišāh ʾālep</em> — is the most dramatic single-night deliverance in the OT since the Exodus. The &lsquo;angel of YHWH&rsquo; executes divine judgment without any human instrument. Eph 4:8, quoting Ps 68:18, applies the divine warrior imagery to Christ&rsquo;s ascension: <em>anabas eis hypsōs ēchmalōteusen aichmalōsian, edōken domata tois anthrōpois</em> — &lsquo;when he ascended on high he led a host of captives.&rsquo; And 1 Cor 15:54-55 announces the final version: death swallowed up in victory. The night the angel destroyed Sennacherib&rsquo;s army is the type; Easter morning, when the last enemy began to be dismantled, is the antitype.</p>",
    "36": "<p class=\"christ-shadow\">Sennacherib departs and dwells at Nineveh — <em>wayyaʿal wayyēlek wayyāšāḇ šannᵉḥerîḇ melek ʾaššûr wayyēšeḇ bᵉnînᵉwēh</em>. The proud king who threatened Jerusalem withdraws to his capital without conquering the city. Jas 4:7 names the principle: <em>antistēte de tō diabolō kai pheuxetai aph&rsquo; hymōn</em> — &lsquo;resist the devil, and he will flee from you.&rsquo; Jesus models this resistance at the temptation (Matt 4:10: <em>hypage, Satana</em> — &lsquo;be gone, Satan&rsquo;) and definitively at the resurrection, where the accuser&rsquo;s claim is annulled. The devil who threatened Christ&rsquo;s people, like Sennacherib who threatened Jerusalem, departs when God acts.</p>",
    "37": "<p class=\"christ-theme\">The chapter ends with Sennacherib&rsquo;s assassination by his sons while he worships in the house of Nisroch his god — killed in the act of worship, killed by his own sons, killed and replaced by another son (Esarhaddon). The proud king who mocked the God of Israel dies within his own idol-temple by family betrayal. The pattern of the destroyer destroyed from within, the proud undone by pride, recurs as a NT principle: <em>ho theos hyperēphanois antitassetai</em> — God opposes the proud (Jas 4:6; 1 Pet 5:5). Christ wins not by killing his enemies but by dying — and in dying defeats death itself. Sennacherib&rsquo;s death by the sword in his god&rsquo;s house is the grotesque parody of what it means for a king to die; Christ&rsquo;s death on the cross is its redemptive fulfilment.</p>"
  },
  "20": {
    "1": "<p class=\"christ-direct\">Isaiah&rsquo;s word to the sick Hezekiah — <em>ṣaw lᵉḇêtᵉḵā kî mēt ʾattāh wᵉlōʾ tiḥyeh</em>, &lsquo;set your house in order, for you shall die; you shall not recover&rsquo; — is the definitive word of mortality spoken to the best of the Davidic kings at the height of his faithfulness. Even Hezekiah&rsquo;s superlative fidelity (18:5) does not exempt him from death. Rev 1:17-18 sets the contrast in Christ&rsquo;s own words: <em>mē phobou; egō eimi ho prōtos kai ho eschatos kai ho zōn, kai egenomēn nekros, kai idou zōn eimi eis tous aiōnas tōn aiōnōn, kai echō tas kleidas tou thanatou kai tou hadou</em> — &lsquo;do not fear; I am the first and the last, and the living one. I died, and behold I am alive forevermore, and I have the keys of Death and Hades.&rsquo; The word &lsquo;you shall die&rsquo; is the universal human condition; Christ alone holds the keys of Death and reverses it.</p>",
    "2": "<p class=\"christ-type\">Hezekiah&rsquo;s response — turning his face to the wall and praying — is the posture of a king who has nowhere to turn except to God. The turning of the face is not despair but orientation: he pivots from the visible world (Isaiah, the sickroom) toward the invisible God. Matt 26:39 narrates Jesus in Gethsemane: <em>kai proselthōn mikron epesen epi prosōpon autou proseuchomenos kai legōn, Pater mou, ei dynaton estin, pareltheto ap&rsquo; emou to potērion touto; plēn ouch hōs egō thelō all&rsquo; hōs sy</em> — &lsquo;falling on his face he prayed, Father, if it be possible, let this cup pass from me; nevertheless, not as I will, but as you will.&rsquo; Both king and King, facing death, turn to the Father with prayer. Hezekiah&rsquo;s prayer is answered with extension of life; Jesus&rsquo;s prayer is answered through death and resurrection.</p>",
    "3": "<p class=\"christ-type\">Hezekiah&rsquo;s prayer rehearses his fidelity: <em>ʾānāh YHWH zᵉḵār nāʾ ʾēt ʾăšer hiṯhallaḵtî lᵉpānêḵā beʾemet ûḇᵉlēḇāḇ šālēm</em>, &lsquo;please, O LORD, remember how I have walked before you in faithfulness and with a wholehearted heart, and have done what is good in your sight.&rsquo; The prayer is theologically legitimate but incomplete as a ground for salvation: Hezekiah appeals to his own record, which is genuinely good but bounded. Christ&rsquo;s ground before the Father is categorically different: John 8:29 records Jesus&rsquo;s claim — <em>egō ta aresta autō poiō pantote</em> — &lsquo;I always do the things that please him.&rsquo; Hezekiah can say &lsquo;I have walked&rsquo;; only Christ can say &lsquo;I always do.&rsquo; Christ intercedes not on the ground of his people&rsquo;s record but on his own.</p>",
    "4": "<p class=\"christ-type\">The speed of God&rsquo;s response — <em>wayhî yᵉšaʿyāhû lōʾ yāṣāʾ hāʿîr hattîḵônāh ûdᵉḇar YHWH hāyāh ʾēlāyw lēʾmōr</em>, &lsquo;before Isaiah had gone out of the middle court, the word of the LORD came to him&rsquo; — is remarkable: the prophet has not left the palace complex before God&rsquo;s answer arrives. John 11:41-42 shows Jesus at Lazarus&rsquo;s tomb praying with the assurance that God &lsquo;always hears&rsquo;: <em>egō de ēdein hoti pantote mou akoueis</em>. Heb 5:7 says Jesus&rsquo;s prayer &lsquo;was heard&rsquo; (<em>eisakoustheis</em>). The immediacy of God&rsquo;s answer to Hezekiah&rsquo;s prayer is a type of the immediacy that characterises the Son&rsquo;s access to the Father — the intermediary stage (prophetic messenger making his way through courtyards) is eliminated in Christ.</p>",
    "6": "<p class=\"christ-direct\">The promise — <em>wᵉyāsaptî ʿal yāmêḵā ḥāmēš ʿeśrēh šānāh</em>, &lsquo;I will add fifteen years to your life&rsquo; — grants Hezekiah extended biological life. The addition of years is the best the OT salvific framework can offer the dying king: more of the same, deferred death. Jesus&rsquo;s promise in John 10:28 is categorically different: <em>kagō didōmi autois zōēn aiōnion, kai ou mē apolōntai eis ton aiōna</em> — &lsquo;I give them eternal life, and they will never perish.&rsquo; And John 11:25-26: <em>egō eimi hē anastasis kai hē zōē; ho pisteuōn eis eme kan apothanē zēsetai</em> — &lsquo;I am the resurrection and the life; whoever believes in me, though he die, yet shall he live.&rsquo; The fifteen added years of Hezekiah are a shadow of the eternal life that Christ gives, which is not extension but transformation.</p>",
    "7": "<p class=\"christ-shadow\">The fig-poultice sign — Isaiah commanding &lsquo;take a cake of figs and apply it to the boil, that he may recover&rsquo; — is healing accomplished through an earthly, humble, non-miraculous material. God does not send an angel or a lightning bolt; he uses a compress of pressed figs. Jesus&rsquo;s healings similarly use bodily media: mud made from spittle (John 9:6), touch (Matt 8:3), saliva (Mark 7:33), the edge of a garment (Matt 9:20). The incarnational principle runs throughout: God works through the material, through the humble, through what is at hand. 1 John 1:1-2 insists on the physicality of the Word of life — <em>ho heōrakamen tais ophthalmois hēmōn, ho etheasametha kai hai cheires hēmōn epsēlaphēsan</em> — &lsquo;what we have seen with our eyes, what we looked upon and have touched with our hands.&rsquo;</p>",
    "8": "<p class=\"christ-type\">Hezekiah&rsquo;s request for a sign — &lsquo;what shall be the sign that the LORD will heal me?&rsquo; — is not rebuked (unlike Ahaz&rsquo;s refusal to ask in Isa 7:12) because it is a request for confirmation of a word already given, not a demand for proof before belief. Jesus responds to the demand for signs with a single offer: Matt 12:39-40 — <em>sēmeion ou dothēsetai autē ei mē to sēmeion Iōna tou prophētou... houtōs estai ho hyios tou anthrōpou en tē kardia tēs gēs treis hēmeras kai treis nyktas</em> — &lsquo;no sign will be given to this generation except the sign of Jonah; so will the Son of Man be three days and three nights in the heart of the earth.&rsquo; The sign of Hezekiah (sundial reversal) and the sign of Jonah (death and resurrection) are both resurrection-shaped: death reversed, time undone, the impossible made actual.</p>",
    "9": "<p class=\"christ-theme\">The offer of the sign — &lsquo;this shall be the sign to you from the LORD, that the LORD will do the thing that he has promised: shall the shadow go forward ten steps, or go back ten steps?&rsquo; — sets Hezekiah before a choice: advance or reversal, the natural or the supernatural. Hezekiah chooses the reversal because advancing is &lsquo;an easy thing.&rsquo; Rev 1:8 presents Christ as the one who encompasses all temporal directions: <em>egō eimi to Alpha kai to Omega, legei Kyrios ho theos, ho ōn kai ho ēn kai ho erchomenos, ho pantokratōr</em> — &lsquo;I am the Alpha and Omega, says the Lord God, who is and who was and who is to come, the Almighty.&rsquo; The one who governs time forward and backward is the one through whom all history is ordered.</p>",
    "10": "<p class=\"christ-shadow\">The shadow going backward on the sundial of Ahaz — <em>wayyāšeḇ haṣṣēl ʿăśāḏāh maʿălôt bamaʿălôt ʾăšer yāraḏāh</em>, &lsquo;so the shadow turned back ten steps, by the steps that it had gone down&rsquo; — is a sign of reversal at the level of natural law. Time itself, as marked by the sun&rsquo;s shadow, is made to run backward as a sign of divine life against death. The resurrection of Jesus is the ultimate reversal of natural law: death, the one-way direction of all biological life, is run in reverse. Rom 6:9: <em>eidotes hoti Christos egertheis ek nekrōn ouketi apothnēiskei; thanatos autou ouketi kyrieuei</em> — &lsquo;we know that Christ, being raised from the dead, will never die again; death no longer has dominion over him.&rsquo; The shadow that went back ten steps is the type of the death that was reversed on the third day.</p>",
    "11": "<p class=\"christ-shadow\">Isaiah calls to YHWH and the shadow goes backward — <em>wayyiqrāʾ yᵉšaʿyāhû hannāḇîʾ ʾel YHWH wayyāšeḇ ʾet haṣṣēl bamaʿălôt ʾăšer yāraḏāh bᵉmaʿălôt ʾāḥāz ʾăḥōrannît ʿeśer maʿālôt</em>. The prophetic word undoes the movement of the natural world. John 11:43-44 shows Jesus commanding Lazarus: <em>Lazare, deuro exō. exēlthen ho tethnēkōs dedemenōs tous podas kai tas cheiras keiriais</em> — &lsquo;Lazarus, come out. The man who had died came out.&rsquo; The prophet&rsquo;s word turns back time&rsquo;s shadow; the Son&rsquo;s word calls back the dead from Hades. In both cases the word is the instrument of the impossible reversal. Hezekiah&rsquo;s sign points to the greater sign that all the resurrection narratives describe.</p>",
    "12": "<p class=\"christ-theme\">The embassy of Berodach-Baladan of Babylon — letters and a gift for Hezekiah because he had been sick — represents a distant power sending tribute and honour to the recovering king. Matt 2:1-12 narrates Magi from the east bringing gifts to the newborn King of kings: gold, frankincense, myrrh — and prostrating themselves before him. The pattern of distant nations bearing tribute to the true king is the messianic expectation of Ps 72:10: <em>malkê ṯaršîš wᵉʾiyyîm minhāh yāšîḇû malkê šᵉḇāʾ ûśᵉḇāʾ ʾeškār yaqrîḇû</em> — &lsquo;the kings of Tarshish and of the islands render him tribute; the kings of Sheba and Seba bring gifts.&rsquo; What the Babylon embassy does for Hezekiah is a pale anticipation of what the Magi do for Christ.</p>",
    "13": "<p class=\"christ-type\">Hezekiah&rsquo;s fatal decision — showing the Babylonian envoys &lsquo;all his treasure house, the silver, the gold, the spices, the precious oil, his armory, all that was found in his storehouses&rsquo; — is a pride-driven full disclosure that opens the kingdom to future plunder. The antitype is Christ&rsquo;s kenosis: Phil 2:7 — <em>alla heauton ekenōsen morphēn doulou labōn</em> — &lsquo;he emptied himself, taking the form of a servant.&rsquo; Hezekiah empties his storehouses for the wrong reason (pride, seeking Babylonian admiration) and to the wrong audience (future captors); Christ empties himself for the right reason (love, obedience) and for the right beneficiaries (those who were lost). The two treasure-emptyings are moral inverses.</p>",
    "14": "<p class=\"christ-theme\">Isaiah&rsquo;s diagnostic question — &lsquo;what did these men say? And from where did they come?&rsquo; — followed by Hezekiah&rsquo;s answer &lsquo;they came from a far country, from Babylon&rsquo; — is the moment of exposure before the prophetic word. The prophet&rsquo;s question functions as a mirror, revealing what Hezekiah has done. John 2:24-25 shows Jesus needing no such question: <em>autos de Iēsous ouk episteuen heauton autois dia to auton ginōskein pantas, kai hoti ou chreian eichen hina tis martyrēsē peri tou anthrōpou</em> — &lsquo;Jesus on his part did not entrust himself to them, because he knew all people and needed no one to bear witness about man, for he himself knew what was in man.&rsquo; The prophet&rsquo;s probing question is the type of Christ&rsquo;s unmediated knowledge of the human heart.</p>",
    "15": "<p class=\"christ-type\">Hezekiah&rsquo;s confession — &lsquo;all that is in my house they have seen; there is nothing among my treasures that I did not show them&rsquo; — is a report of complete self-disclosure to the Babylonians, the very people who will later carry everything away (v17). The irony is that Hezekiah holds nothing back from those who will exploit it. Christ&rsquo;s self-disclosure is the opposite in motive and outcome: Phil 2:7 kenosis is not boasting to admirers but self-emptying for enemies. 2 Cor 8:9: <em>ginōskete gar tēn charin tou kyriou hēmōn Iēsou Christou, hoti di&rsquo; hymas eptōcheusen plousios ōn, hina hymeis tē ekeinō ptōcheia ploutēsēte</em> — &lsquo;for you know the grace of our Lord Jesus Christ, that though he was rich, yet for your sake he became poor, so that you by his poverty might become rich.&rsquo;</p>",
    "16": "<p class=\"christ-direct\">Isaiah&rsquo;s prophetic summons — <em>šᵉmaʿ dᵉḇar YHWH</em>, &lsquo;hear the word of the LORD&rsquo; — introduces the judgment oracle. The formula is the standard opening of prophetic speech throughout the OT; it marks the shift from human dialogue to divine address. Heb 1:1-2 traces the history of this formula to its culmination: formerly God spoke through prophets; <em>ep&rsquo; eschatou tōn hēmerōn toutōn elalēsen hēmin en hyiō</em> — &lsquo;in these last days he has spoken to us by his Son.&rsquo; And John 1:1: <em>en archē ēn ho logos</em> — the prophetic word that began as &lsquo;hear the word of the LORD&rsquo; is now the Word that is God. The &lsquo;word of the LORD&rsquo; that Isaiah brings is the type; Christ, who is the Word, is the antitype.</p>",
    "17": "<p class=\"christ-shadow\">The exile oracle — <em>hinnēh yāmîm bāʾîm wᵉnuśśāʾ kōl ʾăšer bᵉḇêtᵉḵā... bāḇelāh lōʾ yiwwātēr dāḇār</em>, &lsquo;behold the days are coming when all that is in your house... shall be carried to Babylon; nothing shall be left&rsquo; — is judgment for pride: total loss following total disclosure. The Babylonian exile is the OT&rsquo;s deepest crisis, the complete undoing of the Davidic promise. Jesus at Calvary enters the condition the oracle describes: Matt 27:46 (<em>Eli Eli lema sabachthani</em>) is the cry of the one who has entered the nothing-left condition. God &lsquo;spared not his own Son&rsquo; (Rom 8:32: <em>hos ge tou idiou hyiou ouk epheisato alla hyper hēmōn pantōn paredōken auton</em>). Christ enters the &lsquo;nothing shall be left&rsquo; so that his people might be carried out of it.</p>",
    "18": "<p class=\"christ-shadow\">The oracle&rsquo;s final blow — &lsquo;and some of your sons, who will come from you, whom you will father, will be taken away, and they will be eunuchs in the palace of the king of Babylon&rsquo; — is the severing of dynastic continuity: Hezekiah&rsquo;s sons will not reign but serve as eunuchs in a foreign court. The Davidic line appears to be cut off. Isa 53:10 poses the question about the Servant: <em>wᵉʾim tāśîm ʾāšām napšô yirʾeh zeraʿ yaʾărîḵ yāmîm</em> — &lsquo;when his soul makes an offering for guilt, he shall see his offspring; he shall prolong his days.&rsquo; The Servant who appears cut off sees his seed — a spiritual progeny that no eunuch clause can sever. Gal 3:29: <em>ei de hymeis Christou, ara tou Abraam sperma este, kat&rsquo; epangelian klēronomoi</em> — &lsquo;and if you are Christ&rsquo;s, then you are Abraham&rsquo;s offspring, heirs according to promise.&rsquo;</p>",
    "19": "<p class=\"christ-type\">Hezekiah&rsquo;s response to the judgment oracle — &lsquo;the word of the LORD that you have spoken is good... is it not good if there will be peace and security in my days?&rsquo; — is the short-sighted acceptance of a judgment deferred to his descendants. He is content with <em>šālôm</em> in his own lifetime. Isa 9:6-7 names the one who brings the shalom that does not expire: <em>sar šālôm... lᵉmarbēh hammišrāh ûlᵉšālôm ʾên qēṣ</em> — &lsquo;Prince of Peace... of the increase of his government and of peace there will be no end.&rsquo; Eph 2:14: <em>autos gar estin hē eirēnē hēmōn, ho poiēsas ta amphotera hen</em> — &lsquo;for he himself is our peace, who has made us both one.&rsquo; Hezekiah&rsquo;s peace lasts his lifetime; Christ&rsquo;s peace is the peace without end that the oracle&rsquo;s judgment cannot reach.</p>",
    "20": "<p class=\"christ-theme\">The summary notation — &lsquo;the rest of the acts of Hezekiah, and all his might, and how he made the pool and the conduit and brought water into the city&rsquo; — follows the DtrH&rsquo;s royal death formula and refers to the chronicles. The record of Hezekiah&rsquo;s reign is preserved in a book; the record of Christ&rsquo;s significance exceeds any book. John 21:25: <em>estin de kai alla polla ha epoiēsen ho Iēsous, hatina ean graphētai kath&rsquo; hen, oud&rsquo; auton oimai ton kosmon chōrēsein ta graphomena biblia</em> — &lsquo;now there are also many other things that Jesus did. Were every one of them to be written, I suppose that the world itself could not contain the books that would be written.&rsquo; But Phil 4:3 notes that those who belong to Christ have their names written in &lsquo;the book of life&rsquo; — the only record that matters eternally.</p>",
    "21": "<p class=\"christ-shadow\">The chapter closes with Hezekiah&rsquo;s death and the accession of Manasseh — <em>wayyiškaḇ ḥizqiyyāhû ʿim ʾăḇōtāyw wayyimloḵ mᵉnaššeh bᵉnô taḥtāyw</em>. The best Davidic king dies and is succeeded by the worst: Manasseh&rsquo;s reign (21:1-18) will undo everything Hezekiah accomplished. This succession pattern — faithful king followed by catastrophic reversal — is the DtrH&rsquo;s structural demonstration that no human king can secure the covenant permanently. Heb 1:8 quotes Ps 45:6-7 of Christ: <em>ho thronos sou ho theos eis ton aiōna tou aiōnos, kai hē rhabdos tēs euthytētos rhabdos tēs basileias sou</em> — &lsquo;your throne, O God, is forever and ever.&rsquo; Hezekiah&rsquo;s throne passes to Manasseh; Christ&rsquo;s throne admits no successor. The shadow of Manasseh&rsquo;s accession defines what the eternal kingdom of Christ means by contrast: no deterioration, no reversal, no Manasseh after the resurrection.</p>"
  }
}

data = load_comm('mkt-christ', '2kings')
merge_comm(data, NEW)
save_comm('mkt-christ', '2kings', data)

for ch in ['18', '19', '20']:
    import json
    inter_p = ROOT / 'data' / 'interlinear' / '2kings.json'
    inter = json.loads(inter_p.read_text())
    inter_vs = set(inter.get(ch, {}).keys())
    comm_vs = set(data.get(ch, {}).keys())
    missing = inter_vs - comm_vs
    print(f'  ch{ch}: {len(comm_vs)} verses complete')
    if missing:
        print(f'    MISSING: {sorted(missing, key=int)}')
print('2 Kings christ fill (chs 18–20) done.')
